            <section id="gdp-facts" class="facts__section">
                <h1>In Fiscal Year 2018, federal spending was equal to 20% of the total Gross Domestic Product, or economic activity, of the United States that year ($20.7 trillion).</h1>
                
                <p>Why do we compare federal spending to GDP? One reason is to give a reference point for the size of the federal government, as measured by the amount it spends. The U.S. GDP is much larger than government spending, because it includes all the economic activity of the entire nation. Government spending equates to roughly 1 out of every 5 dollars transacted in a year.</p>

